To determine how long it will take the worker to cycle from home to work, we first calculate the distance of the route using the driving details. The worker drives at an average speed of 20 km/h for 9 minutes. Converting 9 minutes to hours gives:

\[
\text{Time in hours} = \frac{9}{60} = 0.15 \, \text{hours}.
\]

The distance is then calculated using the formula:

\[
\text{Distance} = \text{Speed} \times \text{Time} = 20 \, \text{km/h} \times 0.15 \, \text{hours} = 3 \, \text{km}.
\]

Next, to find the time it takes to cycle the same 3 km at an average speed of 6 km/h, we use the formula:

\[
\text{Time} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Speed}} = \frac{3 \, \text{km}}{6 \, \text{km/h}} = 0.5 \, \text{hours}.
\]

Converting 0.5 hours to minutes:

\[
\text{Time in minutes} = 0.5 \times 60 = 30 \, \text{minutes}.
\]

Thus, it will take the worker 30 minutes to cycle from home to work. The correct answer is:

Answer: A

\]

\[

\]

\[
t = \frac{3 \, \text{km}}{6 \, \text{km/h}} = 0.5 \, \text{hours}.
\]  
Converting this time back to minutes:  
\[
0.5 \, \text{hours} \cdot 60 \, \text{minutes/hour} = 30 \, \text{minutes}.
\]  

Therefore, it will take the worker 30 minutes to cycle from home to work. The correct answer is **A) 30**.
